01:50:33,390 --> 01:50:35,491
[SPEAKER_10]: So it's a substantial component.

1106
01:50:36,531 --> 01:50:36,951
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

1107
01:50:37,011 --> 01:50:41,853
[SPEAKER_10]: But it wouldn't affect you just renovating a few rooms.

1108
01:50:42,553 --> 01:50:42,774
[SPEAKER_00]: Right.

1109
01:50:42,814 --> 01:50:50,397
[SPEAKER_00]: If you renovate your kitchen or a bathroom, you're not going to trigger this.

1110
01:50:51,337 --> 01:50:53,318
[SPEAKER_00]: So this is the residential side of it.

1111
01:50:54,438 --> 01:50:58,940
[SPEAKER_00]: And then there's the, sorry, I think I'm going to skip over a lot of this.

1112
01:51:01,292 --> 01:51:03,513
[SPEAKER_00]: This is some of the details in it.

1113
01:51:03,634 --> 01:51:05,455
[SPEAKER_00]: This is how you can comply.

1114
01:51:05,495 --> 01:51:08,116
[SPEAKER_00]: These are the words that go with the chart up above.

1115
01:51:08,677 --> 01:51:10,698
[SPEAKER_00]: And then there's commercial construction.

1116
01:51:10,718 --> 01:51:16,822
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's where things get much more complicated because there are different types of commercial buildings.

1117
01:51:18,043 --> 01:51:26,468
[SPEAKER_00]: They've split it up into over 20,000 square feet, high ventilation buildings, labs, hospitals, and multifamily.

1118
01:51:27,068 --> 01:51:32,970
[SPEAKER_00]: small commercial buildings and multifamily, just because the buildings are very different.

1119
01:51:33,070 --> 01:51:36,951
[SPEAKER_00]: So something I've been watching is some of the requirements in Cambridge over the years.

1120
01:51:37,711 --> 01:51:42,773
[SPEAKER_00]: And years ago, they voted for net zero for certain kinds of new construction.

1121
01:51:43,153 --> 01:51:55,817
[SPEAKER_00]: And at that time, they had set like 2030 as the goal for net zero for lab buildings, not because they wanted to encourage lab, but because they actually use a huge amount of ventilation and air to be safe.

1122
01:51:57,648 --> 01:51:59,196
[SPEAKER_00]: So here's some of the...

1123
01:52:02,463 --> 01:52:13,365
[SPEAKER_00]: Some of what struck me about making this decision is if you notice there's the updated stretch code column and that we don't really have a choice unless we're gonna repeal the stretch code.

1124
01:52:13,845 --> 01:52:16,145
[SPEAKER_00]: And then there's the opt-in stretch code.

1125
01:52:16,706 --> 01:52:30,028
[SPEAKER_00]: And I noticed that for all these dormitories, fire, police station, libraries, offices, schools, post offices and town halls, greater than 20,000 square feet, same as updated stretch code.

1126
01:52:30,668 --> 01:52:37,092
[SPEAKER_00]: commercial high ventilation buildings and all other buildings greater than 20,000 square feet, same as updated.

1127
01:52:37,633 --> 01:52:40,835
[SPEAKER_00]: Small commercial buildings, same as updated stretch code.

1128
01:52:42,136 --> 01:52:46,299
[SPEAKER_00]: So then there's group R buildings with multiple individual dwelling units.

1129
01:52:46,339 --> 01:52:54,985
[SPEAKER_00]: And I don't actually know what a group R building is, but then there's some more details, compliance paths as noted in the table.

1130
01:52:55,725 --> 01:52:59,628
[SPEAKER_00]: And then it's the additional commercial energy efficiency requirements

1131
01:53:00,173 --> 01:53:04,096
[SPEAKER_00]: where you start to get into there being some differences.

1132
01:53:04,836 --> 01:53:14,003
[SPEAKER_00]: What I was sort of focused on is trying to understand where is there a difference between the opt-in and the regular stretch code?

1133
01:53:14,924 --> 01:53:22,930
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's where we've been sort of looking at it going, and will this make a real difference to buildings in Medford?

1134
01:53:24,675 --> 01:53:32,500
[SPEAKER_00]: and at which point is it just window dressing if we approve it, or is it good to approve it because at least then we're making a statement?

1135
01:53:34,321 --> 01:53:38,743
[SPEAKER_00]: But I don't know, Luke, if you want to speak to any of this.

1136
01:53:38,763 --> 01:53:51,531
[SPEAKER_10]: I'll start by saying I think the group R buildings are residential, so multi-family buildings, and they do have different requirements for multi-family projects.

1137
01:53:52,572 --> 01:54:03,361
[SPEAKER_10]: that essentially say if you do the specialized opt-in code, then essentially passive house becomes a requirement as opposed to just a pathway.

1138
01:54:07,223 --> 01:54:15,590
[SPEAKER_10]: And other than that, I have to say I have not spent as much time looking into the other commercial requirements and what those differences are.

1139
01:54:17,680 --> 01:54:22,283
